<DOCNO> AP890404-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
exxon apologized and promised compensation 
for causing the nations biggest oil spill which on monday forced 
alaska to shut down its 12 million herring fishery in prince 
william sound for the season 
new york state police meanwhile said they expected the 
surrender tuesday of joseph hazelwood the former captain of the 
tanker that spilled 101 million gallons of north slope crude after 
it crashed into bligh reef on march 24 
we have reason to believe hell present himself at the state 
police barracks in east farmingdale said state police spokesman 
trooper craig rubio in a telephone interview monday evening 
an arrest warrant has been issued in alaska for hazelwood the 
huntington ny resident is accused of misdemeanor charges of 
operating a ship while under the influence of alcohol reckless 
endangerment and negligent discharge of oil 
the oil slick has now grown larger than rhode island the state 
fish and game department announced monday that the prince william 
sound herring fishery which generates 12 million in annual 
revenues will not open this year officials have previously closed 
the sounds sablefish and shrimp fisheries 
more than half the spawning habitat used by prince william sound 
herring has been fouled said dennis haanpaa a fisheries biologist 
with the department that bodes ill for both the fish and the 
fishermen who tend to catch herring near their spawning ground 
altogether the prince william sound fishing industry is worth 
more than 150 million annually 
in fullpage advertisements placed in newspapers around the 
country monday exxon chairman lawrence g rawl said i want to 
tell you how sorry i am that this accident took place 
rawls statement also appeared to respond to harsh criticism 
from alaskan officials fishermen and environmentalists who accuse 
exxon of reacting slowly and inadequately to the spill 
we believe that exxon has moved swiftly and competently to 
minimize the effect this oil will have on the environment fish and 
other wildlife he said rawl also offered to meet our 
obligations to all those who have suffered damage from the spill 
four class action lawsuits already have been filed against exxon 
at the outset of what could be years of litigation over the 
accident 
in an interview from the companys headquarters in new york 
exxon president lee r raymond said he hopes the emotional type 
of atmosphere generated by the spill does not prompt congress to 
reject the oil industrys request to drill in protected wildlife 
areas 
however that could be precisely the outcome of the spill 
interior secretary manuel lujan suggested in a speech to the 
national ocean industries association in washington 
if the image of an uncareful and uncaring industry prevails 
among the us public then we can kiss goodbye the domestic oil 
and gas development in the arctic national wildlife refuge 
offshore and in the public lands lujan said 
more than 1000 seabirds and at least 20 sea otters caught in 
the oil have died some found covered with asphalthard oil 
officials said the death toll is probably much higher but they 
have had time to survey only a slice of the sounds 2500 miles of 
coastline 
department of fish and game spokesman jon lyman said monday a 
deer found dead on naked island about 25 miles southwest of the 
tanker had apparently eaten contaminated food an indication of how 
rapidly the spill was spreading 
thats bad news thats the top of the food chain lyman 
said 
on nearby green island hundreds of birds lay along the beach 
as black and lifeless as the oilsmeared rocks around them 
sheltered coves and rocky points usually clamoring with the sound 
of gulls and other shorebirds were silent 
every day its getting a little worse otter rescue 
specialist chris donohoe said as he squatted by a dead sea duck 
you clean a beach up the tide changes and the oil comes right 
back 
oil is so thick that walking on once postcardperfect beaches is 
treacherous and workers wear hardhats to protect against injuries 
from frequent tumbles on rocks oil sprayed by waves splatters 
rocks and driftwood logs high above the tideline beaches smell 
like gas station garages 
in sawmill bay 11 miles west of valdez fishermen said monday 
they battling to keep oil away from 2 million salmon at a hatchery 
a sheen of oil has worked its way inside a plastic boom stretched 
across the bay they said 
exxon officials have conceded that beach cleanup efforts so far 
have been futile but the company said it began a new assault with 
more effective gear more workers and a floating command post 
exxon shipping co president frank iarossi said exxon planned to 
flush beaches by pumping seawater over them then collect oil from 
the water with skimmers 
we intend not to leave until the job is done iarossi said 
we intend to leave prince william sound close to what it was 
before the tragedy 
state officials have blasted exxons effort to scrub beaches as 
dismal and ineffective less than 4 percent of the thick crude has 
been recovered 
the spill has fouled more than 800 miles of shoreline in prince 
william sound and the amount grows each day 
hazelwood 42 was fired by exxon last week the skipper 
admitted drinking before boarding the exxon valdez according to 
court documents blood and urine samples taken nine hours after the 
accident indicated he was drunk 
larry weeks director of criminal prosecution for the state of 
alaska said authorities in alaska have had communication with a 
lawyer in new york representing hazelwood 
the tanker accident forced reductions in the flow of oil through 
the alaskan pipeline which carries nearly onequarter of the 
united states domestic supply of crude oil 
alyeska pipeline service co said the flow was increased sunday 
evening with word from the coast guard that tanker traffic would 
soon be allowed to return to normal 
however the coast guard decided monday to reinstate 
daytimeonly restrictions on oil tanker traffic in prince william 
sound after state officials raised concerns spokesman rick meidt 
said 
night traffic was allowed sunday for the first time since the 
exxon valdez one of the two largest tankers in exxons us fleet 
ran aground but after a monday meeting the coast guard decided to 
again limit traffic until all agencies are satisfied that alyeska 
the operator of the valdez terminal has the equipment to handle 
another spill meidt said 
if something were to happen lets make sure we have enough 
gear there to respond he said 
the pipeline usually carries 2 million barrels of crude a day 
that had been reduced to 800000 barrels a day causing shortages 
at west coast refineries and sending oil prices higher 
by monday morning the pipeline flow had been increased to 13 
million barrels a day spokesman john ratterman said pipeline 
company officials said they didnt expect the latest restrictions 
in tanker traffic to force another cutback in flow 
</TEXT>
