<TEXT>
a barge carrying 160000 gallons of 
lye capsized on the ohio river on monday and authorities were 
trying to salvage the craft without a major spill state and 
federal officials said 
a spokesman for the us coast guard said small amounts of a 50 
percent lye solution also known as sodium hydroxide or caustic 
soda could be seeping through vents in the barge 
common sense tells us you assume theres some seepage said 
lt commander arthur adkins of the us coast guard at huntington 
wva but none has been detected 
because of its high alkalinity lye is considered a hazardous 
chemical that could endanger aquatic life and drinking water 
officials said 
the barge owned by ppg industries inc was one of 15 being 
transported by a tugboat around a sharp bend in the ohio river at 
long bottom ohio and murraysville wva it broke away from the 
other vessels and drifted close to the rocky shore before running 
aground between parkersburg and ravenswood adkins said 
the outer shell of the 195foot barge was punctured by a rock 
shortly before 9 am monday adkins said the space between the 
two hulls flooded and the barge capsized 
kemron laboratories a marietta ohio company hired by ppg 
monday to monitor the incident did not detect an alkalinity 
increase in the water surrounding the barge 
it would almost take a catastrophic release to pose a major 
threat adkins said 
in high concentrations such as the barge is carrying lye will 
burn skin and eyes adkins said swallowing it can be dangerous he 
said 
drinking water could be infected so water intake users 
downstream have been notified he said 
the cleanup and removal of the barge is expected to take several 
weeks ppgs salvage expert from lake charles la was to arrive 
early tuesday adkins said 
