<TEXT>
an agriculture department economist says 
federal emergency aid probably helped stabilize land values in 
the midwest last year after drought ravaged crops across the 
region 
gregory hanson of the departments economic research service 
said that surveys by the farm credit banks of st paul minn 
indicate that land prices did not decline in michigan north dakota 
or wisconsin in june through november last year 
other surveys indicate that farmland prices rose in the corn 
belt in 1988 he said real estate is the main source of loan 
collateral for farmers 
while drought assistance has helped stabilize the agricultural 
economy the usda estimates that 10000 to 15000 commercial farms 
faced loan repayment problems due to crop losses hanson said 
these stressed farmers represent 15 percent to 25 percent of 
all commercial farms 
the disaster assistance act of 1988 was signed into law last 
aug 11 as the scorching summer drought was still at its peak the 
law provided up to 39 billion in federal aid and other measures 
to help farmers recover 
hanson writing in the april issue of agricultural outlook 
magazine said that federal disaster assistance may turn out to be 
less than foreseen last fall because crop losses were smaller 
than expected 
also qualification for drought assistance was based on the 
wholefarm average yield for each crop rather than on a 
fieldbyfield basis he said the averagingup of yields 
where good fields offset poorer fields excluded some farmers from 
qualifying in areas with scattered rainfall 
even so hanson added the combination of drought assistance and 
federal subsidized crop insurance has permitted thousands of 
farmers in hardhit states to survive last years bad weather with 
less financial suffering than had been anticipated 
hanson said a full assessment of federal drought aid and 
insurance benefits cannot be completed until all payments and 
indemnities have been disbursed but preliminary figures show those 
had substantial stabilizing effects in the hardesthit drought 
areas 
but on capitol hill there have been grumblings that usda has 
mishandled 1988 relief and has ignored drought conditions now 
prevailing in parts of the great plains notably in kansas and 
parts of texas 
department officials testified that more than 558000 producers 
had received disaster payments and emergency feed assistance 
amounting to more than 27 billion nationally 
in his report hanson said that as of early february more than 
2 billion in drought payments and almost 1 billion in federal 
crop insurance benefits had been paid to farmers in the top eight 
states 
farmers in montana and the dakotas where more than 80 percent 
of the commercial farms were in droughtstricken counties have 
received nearly a third of the drought payments made so far 
benefits paid to the eight states as of early february in 
millions of dollars included drought aid in the first column 
federal crop insurance in the second and the total in the third 
