the agriculture department says the us dry 
bean situation has completely reversed itself from a year ago 
because of higher prices prompted by the 1988 drought 
by january the average farm price of dry edible beans was 
2960 per hundredweight up from 1340 a year earlier 
price increases were the greatest for beans hit hardest by the 
drought for example grower prices for navy beans in the week of 
jan 24 averaged 32 per hundredweight compared with around 10 in 
january 1988 the departments economic research service said 
total us output of dry beans dropped 26 percent to 192 
million hundredweight last year the agency reported 
the sharpest decreases in production were for red kidney 
pintos and navies the beans grown in states with less 
irrigation the report said 
another price factor is an improved outlook for bean exports 
because of poor harvests in several major importing countries 
including mexico and japan 
domestic demand for beans could also improve this year because 
of recent media attention and industry promotional efforts the 
report said beans are a nutritious food item and are noted for 
their fiber content 
