<TEXT>
congress this week celebrates a curious but 
important milestone the 200th anniversary of the days on which the 
first house and first senate achieved a quorum and were finally 
ready to begin the work of the new nation 
the house marks the occasion today april 4 three days after 
the actual april 1 anniversary the senate celebrates on thursday 
april 6 the actual date of its first working quorum 
commemorative postage stamps will be issued honoring the 
bicentennials of both houses 
the congress established under the constitution first convened 
in new york city on march 4 1789 
but the absence of the required majority plus one prevented the 
two chambers from getting down to business 
on that first day only 13 of the 59 house members and only eight 
of the 22 senators were in attendance 
election complications bad weather muddy roads and just plain 
sloth get the blame as causes for the delay 
the journal of the house noted with monotonous regularity that 
a quorum of the members not being present the house adjourned 
congress under the discarded articles of confederation had been 
noted for absenteeism and near paralysis and many feared history 
was about to repeat itself 
we lose credit spirit everything rep fisher ames of 
massachusetts wrote to a friend in boston the public will forget 
the government before it is born 
the senators who had managed to reach new york wrote to their 
absent colleagues we apprehend that no arguments are necessary 
to evince to you the indispensable necessity of putting the 
government into immediate operation and therefore ernestly request 
that you will be so obliging as to attend as soon as possible 
george washington had been elected the nations first president 
but could not enter office until the senate achieved a quorum and 
met to count the ballots of the electoral college 
from mount vernon he grumbled that senators and house members 
were in a state of stupor or listlessness 
but eventually the required numbers assembled 
the house counting its first quorum on april 1 april fools 
day some have noted elected frederick augustus muhlenberg of 
pennsylvania as its first speaker 
and fisher ames much mollified now that work could begin said 
he was pleased with his new colleagues 
while there were few shining geniuses he said there were 
many who had experience the virtues of the heart and habits of 
business 
on april 6 the senate counted its first quorum 
the first order of business counting the votes of the electors 
and dispatching messengers to inform washington and john adams that 
they had indeed been chosen president and vice president 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the postage stamp honoring the senate will display the gilt 
shield and eagle suspended over the presiding officers chair in 
the capitols old senate chamber in use from 1810 to 1859 
the stamp honoring the house of representatives features the 
fanciful car of history a winged marble chariot which since 
1819 has borne the carved figure of clio the muse of history 
over the floor of the old house chamber now statuary hall 
rep john quincy adams who served 17 years in the house after 
his single term as president was inspired in 1840 to dedicate a 
poem to the muse who is shown recording in a book the events 
unfolding on the floor of the legislative body below 
often at odds with his colleagues and irritated by their 
conduct adams paid tribute to the muse for putting up with the 
wordy war conducted by the members 
there was wit there was wisdom he acknowledged but there was 
also the conflicting jar of ranting raving parties day and 
night 
adams concluded 
oh muse historic in thy march sublime 
still urging onward on the wheels of time 
canst thou not whisper to the chosen band 
but for one day to calm their senseless rage 
and let thy volume bear one blessed page 
of deeds devoted to their native land 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lawrence l knutson covers congress and its lore 
for the associated press 
</TEXT>
