<TEXT>
the united states is challenging the worlds 
democratic powers to move quickly and put in motion the bush 
administrations plan for easing the third worlds politically 
explosive debt burden 
treasury secretary nicholas bradys proposals to ease the 
sevenyearold debt crisis were slated for a final review today 
from the executive committee of the international monetary fund and 
the world bank 
some participants at the spring meeting of the two organizations 
have expressed concerns that unless action is taken on the brady 
plan political unrest could be unleashed in the fragile 
democracies of latin america where the huge debt burden has 
depressed living standards for most of this decade 
at least 270 people were killed in riots in venezuela in 
february after the goverment imposed a new austerity program to 
satisfy creditors 
brady in an address on monday told the organizations it was 
time to turn these concepts into specifics which provide a basis 
for lasting progress in dealing with the debt problem 
bradys scheme marks a sharp turn from past us policy because 
it seeks for the first time to reduce the 13 trillion third world 
debt by getting commercial banks to voluntarily forgive part of 
their loans 
although americas allies were not in total agreement with every 
element of the plan canadian finance minister michael wilson 
predicted it would receive general approval 
he told reporters that although much discussion had gone on 
about the technical problems of putting the plan in motion there 
are no serious objections that have been put forward 
the plan got a major boost on monday when the japanese stepped 
forward with a pledge to provide up to 45 billion in new loans to 
third world debtors over the next several years the funds 
however did not match the widely anticipated 5 billion to 10 
billion expected from the tokyo government 
brady also had been counting on other countries running large 
trade surpluses such as west germany to recycle a part of their 
wealth into increased aid for developing nations 
britains chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson made clear 
there were some doubts about how completely the us plan would be 
adopted saying its proposal to use world bank and imf resources to 
guarantee interest payments raised all sorts of problems 
lawson said the time had come for the commercial banks who had 
made the loans to do more to resolve the crisis by writing off debt 
without trying to shift the burden onto the backs of the 
international lending organizations 
the imf and world bank are supported by taxpayer funds from the 
151member countries but the united states is the largest 
contributor 
what i do not find acceptable is the idea that our taxpayers 
should bail out the commercial banks lawson told reporters at a 
briefing 
the two large international lending agencies have a key role to 
play in the plan because they would be expected to put up about 12 
billion each to guarantee to the banks that the remaining part of 
the debt or the annual interest payments would be repaid 
the administration won general approval for its new approach 
from its six largest allies on sunday but the communique issued by 
the united states japan west germany britain france canada and 
italy promised only to examine the question of guaranteeing 
interest payments to the banks 
the group of sevens communique was more supportive of the less 
costly idea of guaranteeing the reduced level of debt 
mailson ferreira da nobrega finance minister of brazil the 
largest third world debtor with 110 billion owed praised the 
brady initiative calling it a major conceptual breakthrough 
with success depending on our capacity to move quickly and far 
enough 
these new ideas raise new hopes he said in his comments to 
the imf steering group they should be translated into immediate 
action it is crucial that such new hopes do not give place to new 
frustrations 
</TEXT>
