gov evan bayh said today that he will 
abolish indianas specialassignment prison release program which 
has been criticized since a furloughed inmate was accused of 
killing his exwife 
bayh also endorsed a recommendation from a sevenmember 
department of correction panel to establish a bill of rights to 
better protect crime victims and witnesses 
bayh ordered the panels study after alan matheney was charged 
with fatally beating his exwife march 4 while on an eighthour 
pass from the correctional industrial complex in pendleton 
matheney was serving an eightyear prison sentence for battering 
lisa marie bianco he now faces murder and burglary charges in her 
death and could face the death penalty if convicted on both counts 
authorities say neither bianco nor the st joseph county 
prosecutor were told that matheney would be released on a pass 
despite their requests for notification 
the panel led by corrections commissioner james e aiken 
recommended the abolishment of the special assignment program 
which allows certain inmates who are not near the end of their 
prison terms to work in the community during the day those inmates 
also have been allowed unescorted leaves of up to 48 hours once a 
month 
the panel also recommended tighter controls on eligibility 
requirements for other minimumsecurity programs and closer 
monitoring of offenders criminal histories 
the priority is to protect the public aiken said noting 
that the corrections department is looking now at where the inmates 
who no longer qualify for prison release programs will be housed 
during the next 180day crunch period 
almost 400 inmates involved in the three minimumsecurity 
programs will be sent back to the general prison population because 
of the drastically tightened eligibility requirements bayh 
said 
the panel also recommended that offenders not be allowed to 
leave a work release center except for employment or educational 
purposes without a leave approved by the director the panelists 
also suggested random telephone calls to ensure that offenders 
released into the community shortly before their terms are 
completed are following department rules 
