the nato alliance shaped out of the 
fears of soviet expansionism turned 40 on tuesday with western 
officials expressing caution and uncertainty about the dramatic 
changes gripping the soviet union 
manfred woerner secretarygeneral of the 16nation north 
atlantic treaty organization said the soviet union will still 
remain a strong military power even if promised cuts are carried 
out in troops and military spending 
the intentions of the current soviet leadership are 
peaceful ones woerner told a news conference at nato 
headquarters in brussels soviet president mikhail s gorbachev he 
said doesnt want to wage a war 
but he cautioned there is still a risk because intentions may 
change we have no control over them personalities leaders may 
change 
woerners remarks capped a morning of ceremonies marking the 
signing of the nato treaty on april 4 1949 forming a security 
alliance that links the united states and canada with western 
european nations the western nations joined the pact to unite 
against the threat of expansionism posed by moscow in the years 
following world war ii 
gorbachevs recent agenda of economic and social reforms and his 
promises of military cuts have diminished the publics perception 
of that threat and raised questions about natos role 
anniversary speeches celebrations and a few protests held 
elsewhere in europe reflected the new situation 
british defense secretary george younger in a speech at nato 
offices north of london credited the alliance with helping bring 
about the long overdue changes under way in eastern europe 
five members of the christian campaign for nuclear disarmament 
demonstrated outside the nato complex undeterred by a rare spring 
sprinkling of snow nato officials served them hot tea 
in oslo norwegian prime minister gro harlem brundtland called 
nato the most successful alliance we know and foreign minister 
thorvald stoltenberg called it more important than ever 
a small group of protesters in rome including greens party 
