<TEXT>
the air force has discovered a problem with 
lubricant levels in a wing gear box on its b1b bomber fleet that 
is slowing the return of the bombers to the air the pentagon said 
tuesday 
dan howard the pentagons chief spokesman said the strategic 
air command had cleared the b1b bomber fleet to return to flight 
status on sunday as individual planes underwent a final safety 
check and more than 35 of the planes would be flying tuesday 
during the course of the final safety checks however air force 
mechanics began discovering a problem with gear boxes that are part 
of the assembly to move the wings back and forth the spokesman 
continued 
howard said the air force now expects roughly 90 of the b1bs 
to be certified for flight operations by the weekend 
the problem involves a loss of the lubricant contained inside a 
sealed gear box that handles what is known as the angle gear drive 
shaft howard said that angle gear drive shaft is a key component 
of the wingmoving assembly 
according to the air force of 80 b1bs receiving the final 
safety inspection so far 70 showed insufficient lubricant levels 
inside that gear box 
howard denied tuesday the air force had uncovered any evidence 
showing that a loss of lubricant in that gear box was the cause of 
a march 27 incident that led to a weeklong grounding of the b1b 
fleet 
in that incident a b1b undergoing a preflight check at dyess 
air force base texas suffered a tear in a fuel tank when the left 
wing swung too far forward 
howard disclosed tuesday that accident investigators probing the 
mishap had discovered a fractured quill shaft in a main wing 
gear box and a fractured angle gear drive shaft 
other sources who insisted on anonymity said the air force 
does now suspect that a lubricant seal problem led to the march 
27 mishap probably by allowing too much torque pressure to build 
up on the shaft 
at first blush thats exactly what we believe caused the wing 
to go too far said one source theres a very definite 
connection 
howard referring to the two fractured shafts said we dont 
know what sequence those occurred in 
we dont know what the first cause was yet whether it was a 
procedural problem a maintenance problem or a hardware problem 
but simply in the course of investigating every possible problem 
that they could have had they did discover this potential problem 
with the lubricant 
the air force said the sealed gear boxes were manufactured by 
the sundstrand corp and when mechanics were finding one with 
insufficient lubricant it was being replaced and sent off to the 
contractor for repair 
i think its fortunate we had the incident at dyess on the 
ground because that led to the kind of detailed investigation that 
enabled us to catch something that we might not have caught 
added one air force source 
the fourengine b1b is the first addition to the manned bomber 
force in more than 25 years to improve its performance the plane 
features wings that can be swept forward or backward in flight the 
wings are normally swept back for highspeed attack runs and 
forward for takeoffs and landings 
built by the rockwell international corp the b1b has a 
maximum speed of about 1000 mph and a range of more than 7000 
miles 
the air force built 100 of the planes during the reagan 
administration to modernize the old b52 bomber force while it 
developed the new b2 stealth bomber three b1bs have been lost 
in accidents leaving 97 in the fleet 
