<TEXT>
the rights of television viewers are being 
trampled by laissezfaire federal regulators who no longer require 
tv stations to broadcast public affairs programming consumer 
advocate ralph nader said tuesday 
nader appearing at a news conference to discuss a study that 
said there has been a 51 percent decrease in issuesoriented public 
affairs tv programs since 1979 called for reinstatement of the 
fairness doctrine and requirements that broadcasters devote certain 
percentages of their broadcasting hours to nonentertainment 
programming 
the federal communications commission in 1987 repealed the 
40yearold fairness doctrine which had required broadcasters to 
cover controversial issues in 1984 the fcc revoked rules that 
obligated broadcasters to alot 5 percent of their programming 
between 6 am and midnight to local shows 5 percent to news and 
public affairs programs and 10 percent to general interest items 
such as as gardening religion and advicetype shows 
nader said the fcc under chairman dennis r patrick and his 
predecessor mark s fowler was a rogue agency that has 
dangerously transformed power from the public to private commerce 
in sheer violation of the 1934 communications act 
nader said fowlers view was audiences have no first amendment 
rights fowler and now patrick maintained that marketplace 
pressures would force station owners to broadcast issuesoriented 
programs 
that has not happened nader said and the fcc refuses to 
respect the access rights the response rights of the audience 
nader said that the fcc has abdicated its responsibility to 
monitor the broadcasting industry and that if it had it would have 
found an erosion of public interest programming in the wake of the 
1984 repeal of the socalled 5510 guidelines 
the study by essential information a public interest group that 
nader founded in 1982 examined tv listings for programs at 217 
stations in 50 markets on seven days in early 1988 
the listings were compared with fccrequired program logs from 
1975 1978 and 1979 the study did not include cable tv 
jim donahue who wrote the study said the results show a 51 
percent decrease between 1979 and 1988 in the average percentage of 
issueoriented public affairs programming 
he also said that the average percentage of time devoted to 
public affairs has decreased 39 percent with 30 percent of abc 
cbs and nbc affiliates and 63 percent of fox broadcasting 
affiliates neglecting to air a locally produced public affairs 
program 
donahues study also showed there has been an 74 percent 
increase in news programs and sharp increases in home shopping 
real estate and programlength commercials such as how to lose 
weight or get rich 
fcc spokesman john kamp said the report sounds terribly bogus 
we have increased the number of stations over the last 10 years 
both television and radio by half and news and public affairs 
programming makes money i find it incredible to think that the 
amount of this programming would go down so i dont know how he 
counted it but i think its subect to being recounted 
regarding the fairness doctrine kamp said the commission 
found that it decreased the amount of public interest programming 
available which was the opposite of what it was intended to 
do 
