a court on tuesday convicted an 
activist for distributing leaflets and sentenced him to four months 
in prison tuesday and an appeals court upheld sentences for seven 
others in a crackdown on dissent 
the court in the central city of brno convicted jarolsav popelka 
of disturbing public order said dissident sources in prague 
popelka 32 was arrested march 24 he had handed out flyers 
last year calling for the resignation of a hardline communist 
leader and for genuine reforms and environmental protection 
also on tuesday judge jan roit upheld convictions against jana 
petrova a 22yearold peace activist and ota veverka 32 
stemming from banned protests in january said charter 77 activist 
anna sabatova on feb 22 ms petrova was sentenced to nine months 
in prison and sabatova received 12 months in prison 
ms petrova and veverka were among dissidents who tried to lay 
flowers jan 16 in wenceslas square in memory of jan palach a 
student who burned himself alive 20 years earlier to protest the 
presence of soviet troops in his homeland following the 1968 
invasion that crushed communistled reforms 
the appeal hearing also left unchanged suspended sentences for 
five other activists charter 77 signatories jana sternova and 
david nemec petr placak of the youth group czech children 
stanislav penc of the john lennon peace club and charter 77 
spokesman alexander vondra they had received suspended sentences 
ranging between two and six months at the feb 22 trial 
