<TEXT>
a glittering collection of gold jewelry and 
ornaments from west africa where gold was shunned in ancient times 
as an evil spirit begins a threeyear ninecity tour of the 
united states on wednesday at the smithsonian institutions 
national museum of african art 
the handiwork of goldsmiths from ghana ivory coast mali and 
senegal comes from the private barbiermueller museum of geneva 
which houses one of the finest collections of african gold 
sculpture in the world 
more than 150 handmade objects comprising about half of the 
barbiermueller collection are going on display at the 
smithsonian they include elaborate necklaces rings hair jewels 
pendants masks earrings beads and ceremonial regalia such as 
golddecorated fly whisks sword handles and staffs 
guest curator timothy garrard a british historian and authority 
on the gold trade in west africa said gold dust and nuggets long 
were regarded with fear by natives who believed they would cause 
blindness and insanity 
africans began their goldsmith traditions in the 5th century 
when european traders alerted by slave merchants sailed down the 
west coast of africa or crossed the sahara desert in caravans from 
north africa to trade salt and spices for gold 
very little of ancient west african gold jewelry exists today 
because it was lost in trade looted from burial grounds and melted 
down to make coins or new ornaments garrard said the oldest piece 
in the smithsonian show probably is a fish pendant in pure gold 
about 22 carats from 18th century ghana 
after the show closes at the national museum of african art on 
aug 28 it is scheduled to travel through july 1992 to art museums 
in new york dallas birmingham ala tampa fla chicago 
detroit indianapolis and louisville ky 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

