<TEXT>
when beef began to disappear from 
supermarkets last month and butchers took to the streets against 
illegal price increases many brazilians had a sinking feeling of 
deja vu 
three years ago powerful cattle ranchers defied a nationwide 
price freeze aimed at halting runaway 1000 percent inflation the 
shortages and black marketeering that followed doomed the 
governments plan 
now it seemed to be happening again 
the beef crisis alarmed the government president jose sarney 
called the shortage sabotage and said it threatened the fledgling 
democracy under which brazil on nov 15 will hold its first 
presidential election in 29 years 
brazil will not tolerate speculation fraudulent withholding 
of goods and crimes against the economy sarney said last week 
in a weekly nationwide radio program 
politicking and economic disorganization threaten the 
transition to democracy said sarney a civilian who took office 
in 1985 after 21 years of military rule 
inflation reached 288 percent a month in december then fell to 
3 percent for 11 days in february after the government froze 
prices but the cost of living rose 6 percent in march far above 
government predictions 
problems began soon after sarney on jan 15 announced a national 
wageandprice freeze as part of his summer plan brazils 
fourth antiinflation program in three years 
shortages soon began to occur eggs auto parts and cooking oil 
became scarce as suppliers said they couldnt meet demand at the 
governmentset price the government acted swiftly negotiating a 
tax break for auto industries and seizing 38 million cans of oil 
in a supermarket warehouse 
federal police even detained the supermarkets owner abilio 
diniz president of the pao de acucar chain and one of brazils 
wealthiest businessmen on charges of crimes against the public 
economy 
but the government was impotent against cattlemen for centuries 
a powerful and independent clan in latin americas largest country 
cattle breeders raised the price of beef to wholesalers from 18 
for each 32pound unit in january to 23 in march but wholesalers 
who tried to pass on the higher costs were fined by federal 
pricecheckers and many simply stopped sales altogether 
in many cities butcher shops sold meat on the black market or 
closed their doors supermarkets rationed beef to customers 
butchers in cars and oxcarts marched through downtown sao 
paulo brazils biggest city and financial center to protest the 
price increases riot troops broke up the march with water jets 
colored with pink dye 
the government vowed not to repeat the mistakes of 1986 when 
federal police on horseback and in helicopters tried to find cattle 
allegedly hidden in pastures police caught only a few cows for 
slaughter and the government was ridiculed 
this time officials threatened to ban beef exports and audit 
the tax returns of price violators but the ranchers didnt budge 
in april the government agreed to discuss a price increase for 
meat to save its antiinflation program 
politics and inflation are closely linked in this country of 144 
million past failed attempts to halt inflation caused the 
popularity of sarneys centerright government to plummet and 
helped leftist parties to sharp gains in november municipal 
elections 
</TEXT>
