companies get military contracts 
stuart e berlin who headed an aviation systems branch of the 
navy procurement command made the admission at the trial of three 
teledyne electronics inc executives accused of conspiring to bribe 
him to influence the award of an equipment contract 
berlin testified that he had received at least 2000 in cash 
from a defense consultant in return for providing detailed 
information about an equipment contract teledyne was seeking from 
the pentagon 
on crossexamination defense attorney mark tuohey iii said 
youve been selling your country short for money for 10 years 
i have taken money for 10 years berlin said acknowledging 
receipt of thousands of dollars in payments that tuohey listed 
on direct testimony berlin told jurors that he received two 
1000 cash payments and possibly a third from consultant fred h 
lackner after providing detailed status reports about the 
pentagons decision to buy handheld radar test devices 
berlin who pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy and bribery 
last month said he fed information to lackner during monthly 
meetings they had from mid1985 to june 1988 
everything i knew or could find out about the procurement was 
passed on to mr lackner berlin said he testified that lackner 
told him that he was relaying the information to william l parkin 
a defense consultant retained by teledyne 
but lackner who has also pleaded guilty testified later in the 
day that he received only sporadic reports from berlin and got no 
information at all during 1986 
he was passing this on to mr parkin who was in turn passing 
this on to teledyne berlin said he testified that he had 
expected to receive about 25000 a onefourth share of the 
100000 that parkin was to be paid by teledyne for his services 
but lackner testified that he and parkin and another 
coconspirator agreed to tell berlin they were sharing 100000 
instead of 150000 the amount they expected to receive from 
teledyne adding everyone felt he really didnt do anything to 
aid the procurement 
parkin also pleaded guilty in the case and may testify as a 
prosecution witness against the three defendants george kaub 
eugene r sullivan and dale schnittjer 
the defense contends that the three teledyne executives knew 
nothing about the illegal activities of parkin lackner and michael 
savaides the companys washington lobbyist who has also pleaded 
guilty in the case 
earlier in the day however former teledyne vice president 
william rosen testified that he had attended a meeting during which 
kaub and sullivan agreed to hire parkin and pay him 150000 if 
teledyne obtained the contracts 
rosen conceded on crossexamination that he did not know whether 
the agreement with parkin he helped draft was ever executed 
rosen said he had hired savaides on berlins recommendation 
berlin said lackner had repeatedly over 15 years offered to go 
into business with him proposing arrangements to provide inside 
information to defense contractors for a price 
berlin said he spurned those offers until mid1985 when lackner 
proposed a deal involving teledyne i told him yes that i could 
help him 
during a subsequent meeting lackner said that he did have a 
contact who would work with teledyne and it looked like this could 
be profitable for all of us berlin added 
he told me that it was bill parkin he said bill parkin had a 
relationship with teledyne and could easily get a contract with 
teledyne 
berlin added that lackner said that he needed quantity and 
budget information that would enable teledyne to know the scope 
of the potential contract berlin said he was supposed to keep 
him posted on what was happening in the navy and the air force a 
daily status report 
berlin explained to us district court jurors that much of the 
information he passed to lackner was not supposed to be released to 
the defense industry because it could possibly give one 
competitor an unfair advantage over another 
by the spring of 1987 berlin said that lackner complained that 
he was having difficulty getting paid from teledyne 
the former navy procurement official said that he suggested 
several ways of pressuring teledyne including raising the 
possibility that the contract would be terminated or that the full 
threeyear term of the order would not be completed 
berlin said that lackner told him he was going to threaten 
them with termination of the existing contract and use any leverage 
he could to get paid 
berlin said that six months later lackner reported that he was 
to share a quarter of the 100000 that teledyne had agreed to pay 
