<TEXT>
voters in one out of every eight soviet 
parliamentary districts refused to elect anyone even though they 
had a choice of only one or two candidates according to official 
results released tuesday 
the tass news agency released the central election commissions 
final tally of the votes from march 26 elections for the countrys 
new 2250member congress of peoples deputies 
tass said that in 195 of the 1500 geographical districts across 
the country no one got a majority of the vote even though there 
were only one or two candidates in those districts new electoral 
campaigns will be waged and a second election will be held may 14 
tass said 
election results released earlier showed that in the first 
nationwide multicandidate election in 70 years voters rejected many 
topranking communist party and government leaders they included 
yuri solovyev a candidate member of the ruling politburo who ran 
unopposed in leningrad 
tass said a meeting of leningrad party leaders tuesday led by 
solovyev characterized the election results as a serious 
political lesson 
leningrad residents are not satisfied with the tempo of 
solving the housing problem the equipping of the city the 
ecological situation the agency said they express 
dissatisfaction with the shortage of industrial and food products 
and concern about the growth of crime tass said 
among those who also suffered defeat were the kiev party leader 
and mayor the mayor and secondleading party official in moscow 
and a host of regional party chiefs 
in the majority of cases the reason for this is the striving 
of the people to quicken the process of restructuring more 
actively struggle with bureaucracy and commandadministrative 
methods of work election commission chairman vladimir orlov told 
tass 
boris n yeltsin the former moscow party chief who waged an 
antiestablishment campaign won his race with more than 89 percent 
of the vote 
tass also indicated that party officials met in leningrad on 
tuesday to review the results of the election but no word was 
available on the results of that meeting 
the literary weekly literaturnaya gazeta reported that in at 
least one case a party leaders loss may result in a court case 
the paper said the party leader of alma ata capital of kazakhstan 
was taking his opponent to court for distributing 100000 leaflets 
accusing him of selling deficit items like meat perfume and sugar 
at his election rallies 
vi romanov the alma ata party leader lost the election to a 
safonov the director of a homebuilding enterprise 
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i gerasimov said two days 
after the balloting that party organizations would have to review 
the status of top officials who lost their races he refused to 
characterize the vote as a defeat for the party saying the vast 
majority of those elected were party members 
official figures released tuesday indicated that 876 percent of 
those elected on march 26 were party members 
orlov told tass that nationwide voter turnout was 898 percent 
that high degree of activity gladdens us more than the 
notorious 999 percent participation which we were proud of 
earlier orlov said in this election there was no race for 
percentage of participation the previous mandatory measures 
practiced previously were fully excluded 
in the past the soviet union proclaimed an almost total 
participation in elections as proof of citizens satisfaction even 
though voters werent offered a choice 
tass said runoff elections will be held in another 76 districts 
sunday for seats in which the vote was split among three or more 
candidates such that no one received a majority 
onethird of the new congress will consist of deputies elected 
by the party and its affiliates labor professional and social 
organizations 
tass said 18 of those 750 seats remain to be filled they 
include 12 seats from the academy of sciences where scientists 
rejected most of an old guard list that did not include human 
rights activist andrei d sakharov 
sakharov has been nominated again as a candidate and the academy 
is to decide later this week when a new election will be held 
the final figures indicated that of those elected 171 percent 
were women and 186 percent were workers both figures were lower 
than the composition of the present supreme soviet in which 
authorities have tried to impose quotas 
