the district of columbia council approved an 
emergency antiloitering bill tuesday that would give the citys 
police power to arrest people congregating in designated illegal 
drug zones 
the bill the latest move in the citys attempt to curb 
drugrelated violence allows police to make arrests if those 
gathering in a such a zone refuse to move on when asked to do so 
the mayor has 10 days in which to sign the measure which then 
would be effective for 90 days the police chief would be able to 
designate a place with a history of drug activity over six months 
as an illegal drug zone and to ban congregation in an area of 1000 
square feet for up to 120 hours 
the areas limited to public property such as sidewalks 
streets and publichousing courtyards would be clearly marked by 
signs barriers and police tape the maximum penalty for loitering 
would be 300 or 90 days in jail 
the intent of the bill is to be able to disperse people 
said nadine winter a member of the council 
we recognize that we will have to impede on the rights of 
others in order for us to gain control of our community said 
hr crawford another council member 
