<TEXT>
chemical agents such as those applied in 
response to the vast oil spill in alaskas prince william sound are 
of limited value in major spills but can be effective in dispersing 
smaller slicks according to a study published tuesday 
the study by a national research council panel of academic and 
industry experts said use of dispersants generally is helpful in 
ocean spills but more biological studies are needed to determine 
how coastal habitats are affected by the chemicals 
the research council is an independent adviser to the government 
on scientific issues its study was conducted before last months 
spill of 10 million gallons of crude oil from the exxon valdez the 
largest in us history 
dispersants are most effective when applied to oil within the 
first five hours after a spill the study said adding that a day 
or two of evaporation and weathering cause spilled oil to become 
too thick to disperse with chemicals 
exxons application of a dispersant called corexit was delayed 
for more than a day first because the water was too cold and calm 
then because strong winds that created a better environment for the 
dispersants hampered the aircraft used to spread the chemicals 
applying dispersants quickly is especially important because 
effective alternatives do not exist for treating ocean oil 
spills the council report said 
dispersants usually are made of thick liquid detergent that is 
mixed with a solvent that thins the detergent and makes it easier 
to apply the molecules of the dispersant attach themselves to the 
oil reducing the surface tension between the oil and the water 
this makes it easier for the oil to dissolve in the water 
the report quoted james n butler of harvard university 
chairman of the experts panel as saying the mandate is clear to 
use chemical dispersants when oil must be dispersed before it 
reaches shore 
once oil enters coastal habitats the decision to use chemicals 
is more difficult the study said since fish and shellfish can be 
harmed 
for years chemical dispersants have been suspected by some of 
causing more environmental harm than good the research council 
report said experts who studied a 1967 oil spill off britain in 
which thousands of tons of dispersants were used concluded that the 
chemicals contributed to the deaths of local animals and plants 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

