<TEXT>
more than 200 justice department attorneys 
submitted a petition tuesday to attorney general dick thornburgh 
criticizing the departments attempt to persuade the supreme court 
to overturn the landmark 1973 decision legalizing abortion 
we believe that every woman has the right to make her own 
decision about whether or not to continue her pregnancy in 
accordance with the guidelines set forth in roe vs wade the 
petition said referring to the 1973 case we oppose any 
governmental interference with this basic right 
the petition bearing 248 names most of them attorneys was 
given to thornburghs office late in the afternoon according to 
one of the signers 
dave runkel a top aide to thornburgh said the petition wont 
have any impact on the departments position 
these people come in six months after the decision was made to 
appeal this case to the supreme court he said its not 
timely if they wanted to have an impact on what the department 
was doing on this theyre six months too late 
one of the signers an attorney who spoke only on condition of 
anonymity said the petition was submitted late because attorneys 
at the department are very busy and it took a long time to get the 
organization in motion in addition she said the signers hope the 
petition will make an impact on other cases 
she said thornburgh and the department had involved themselves 
in partisan politics by intervening in the case 
runkel said he didnt expect any retaliation against the people 
who signed the petition saying the attorney general understands 
this is a controversial issue that people disagree on 
i dont anticipate any impact unless people decide that 
they so disagree that they can no longer work here he said 
the case before the supreme court is called webster vs 
reproductive health services and it concerns a missouri law that 
prohibits the use of public funds or public employees from 
encouraging or performing or assisting an abortion the 
8th us circuit court of appeals rejected key portions of the law 
last july 13 
the supreme court could act on the webster case without touching 
the 1973 roe vs wade decision but the justice department in a 
brief filed in february urged the court to overturn its earlier 
ruling and leave decisions on abortions to legislators 
the signer who commented on the petition said the majority of 
those who signed are women 
she said the many female attorneys at justice give the issue 
relevance serving as reminders that their ability to pursue 
careers would be compromised by unwanted pregnancies 
colleen oconnor of the american civil liberties union praised 
the employees who signed the petition 
quite apart from the issue of what the department is doing on 
roe vs wade its heartening to know there are a few government 
lawyers willing to exercise their first amendment rights she 
said 
the attorney general obviously can respond any way he wants to 
that petition but he of all people has to know that his employees 
should not bear any recriminations for expressing their views on an 
issue as important as this one oconnor said 
</TEXT>
