<TEXT>
a state board is expected to rule later this 
week whether former vice president spiro agnew can get a refund on 
his california taxes for money he had to pay to maryland as 
restitution in a kickback case 
agnew is appealing a 1986 denial by the california franchise tax 
board of his request for a refund of 24197 
agnew who pleaded no contest to corruption charges and resigned 
as vice president in 1973 paid 142000 in restitution for 
allegedly accepting bribes from road engineering contractors while 
he was governor of maryland from 1967 to 1969 
the former vice president views the courtordered restitution as 
an expenditure and wants to recover a percentage of it said louis 
bertane senior counsel for the california board of equalization 
the appellate panel 
the boards ruling will be issued thursday the attorney said 
its fairly routine it doesnt present any extremely novel 
legal questions bertane said tuesday 
agnew originally sought the deduction on his 1981 tax return 
filed after he became a resident of rancho mirage and just months 
after he made restitution 
the franchise tax board in 1986 rejected the deduction because 
california has never received any income in the form of taxes or 
otherwise from the amounts agnew allegedly received as bribes 
to approve the deduction the board said would have the effect 
of requiring california taxpayers to subsidize agnews return of 
public monies to the taxpayers of maryland 
agnews lawyer t rogers harrison urged the board of 
equalization to ignore the identity of those involved 
