<TEXT>
this is a metropolis of refugees the 
capital of one country it is filled with palestinians who cherish 
dreams of another country across the jordan river 
amman was a dusty backwater of 35000 people when the first 
arabisraeli war broke out in 1948 that conflict and its 
successor in 1967 flooded jordan with refugees and many of them 
settled in and around the capital 
today about 70 percent of the 12 million residents of amman 
are palestinians making it the largest urban concentration of 
palestinians anywhere 
welleducated palestinians many sending home money from jobs in 
the persian gulf helped make jordan into one of the third worlds 
success stories despite the countrys lack of natural resources 
expensive cars roam ammans streets and spacious houses sprawl 
across its hills shops sell french cheeses italian clothes and 
danish furniture to a population that averaged more than 2000 per 
capita a year in income before an economic recession set in two 
years ago 
the palestinian stamp is evident in the savory aroma of 
palestinian sweets wafting from bakeries and in the elaborately 
embroidered palestinian dresses worn by many women 
young men wear the blackchecked kaffiyeh headdress that has 
become an emblem of the palestinian uprising against israels 
21year occupation of the west bank of the jordan river 
but palestinians in amman find themselves torn between two 
nationalities that of jordan and that of a new palestinian state 
declared in november by the palestine liberation organization 
that conflict led to a war in 1970 and the defeat of palestinian 
guerrillas by jordans bedouin army palestinians refer to the 
supression of the palestinian state within jordan as black 
september 
but for many there is no conflict they hope to remain in 
jordan at least part of the time even if they gain a state in 
palestine 
i dont see that there has to be a choice said hazem 
nuseibeh a former jordanian foreign minister who comes from one of 
jerusalems most prominent palestinian families 
to the contrary i think if there is a solution it will be the 
creation of a jordanianpalestinian confederal union 
isa samaan rantisi 52 an amman grocer expressed gratitude 
toward the country that sheltered his impoverished family some 40 
years ago when it crowded into a oneroom storefront in an amman 
ravine 
they gave us everything here more than any other arab 
country he told a reporter we dont think of ourselves as 
strangers 
but his 18yearold nephew raed shamali like many youths in 
amman said he yearns to go home to a country he has never known 
if i could go i would go its my country we should go 
back said shamali who wore a scarf fringed in the green black 
white and red colors of the palestinian flag as he served customers 
in the crowded store 
in 1950 jordan annexed the west bank and gave the palestinians 
citizenship in jordan but jordan lost the terrority to israel in 
the 1967 arabisraeli war 
king hussein in 1988 renounced claims to the west bank 
declaring jordan is not palestine a reference to proposals 
from israelis that jordan serve as the palestinian state rather 
than let refugees reclaim property in what is now israel 
hussein said palestinians in jordan would have all the rights 
and privileges of jordanian citizens until a palestinian state is 
created 
