<TEXT>
in statehouses across the country lawmakers fear any 
significant alteration to roe vs wade could trigger a political 
war that would make their years as reluctant soldiers in the 
abortion battles seem like a skirmish 
the landmark 1973 us supreme court decision legalizing 
abortion ended most of the fierce struggling over the issue in 
state legislatures but with the court reconsidering the issue 
legislators are worrying about a return to the incessant emotional 
wrangling that preceded the ruling 
if they overturn roe it will be the most tragic thing to 
happen in a long time said rep hl jensen a democrat from 
jackson wyo who is the state house minority floor leader it 
will really be a nightmare 
the high court is scheduled to hear arguments april 26 on 
missouri abortion regulations struck down last july by the 8th us 
circuit court of appeals 
groups on both sides of the issue believe the supreme court 
might use the case to modify if not overturn the roe vs wade 
decision thirtyfour states banned or severely restricted 
abortions in 1973 and 15 states still have antiabortion laws on 
the books although legal experts say it is not clear they could 
take effect if roe vs wade was reversed 
gosh i hope they dont stir that up again it was one of 
the worst things ive been through as a legislator said 
republican rep marvin littlejohn chairman of the kansas house 
public health and welfare committee recalling the preroe days 
when strident signcarrying abortion foes jammed the statehouse to 
protest kansas liberal law 
the appeals court struck down key provisions of the missouri law 
that banned use of public hospitals or public employees for 
abortions prohibited use of taxpayer money for abortion 
counseling required doctors to test a fetus older than 19 weeks 
for viability and declared that life begins at conception 
most states stayed out of the case but a few decided to enter 
the fray 
louisiana which boasts of having the nations most stringent 
antiabortion laws on the books was joined by arizona idaho 
pennsylvania and wisconsin in filing a brief with the supreme court 
supporting missouris position 
massachusetts which won a 1988 court case blocking reagan 
administration efforts to ban abortion at federally financed family 
planning clinics filed a brief arguing against missouri its brief 
was signed by california colorado new york texas vermont and 
west virginia 
most states have adopted a waitandsee attitude but forces on 
both sides of the issue have begun mobilizing support 
im sure if they overturned the decision there will be at 
least a dozen legislators jumping in with bills said russell 
maffei legislative aide to new jersey state sen gerald cardinale 
a recently announced republican candidate for governor it would 
be a knockdown dragout fight decided by halfdozen votes one way 
or the other 
the supreme courts decision in the missouri case expected in 
july would come too late for the battles to begin this year 
instead most legislators see themselves starting the new decade 
under siege if roe vs wade is altered 
that would tie up every legislature in the united states in a 
bitter debate said bradford gorham rhode island house minority 
leader 
for some such as maryland that means the continuation of a 
nowin struggle that began in 1973 to whittle away at roe vs wade 
on a local level last year business stopped for several days in 
the maryland senate while antiabortion lawmakers filibustered a 
budget bill amendment to ease restrictions on medicaid financing of 
abortions 
prochoice legislators hold a one or twovote margin in the 
maryland senate not enough to stop a filibuster but sufficient to 
block antiabortion legislation the result is a stalemate a 
situation not likely to change 
there is a gridlock with very very strong intense views that 
seem not to be able to get either position to move maryland 
attorney general j joseph curran said thats the reality of 
this state 
a reversal by the supreme court likely would trigger new legal 
fights over whether the antiabortion laws still on the books in 15 
states could take effect 
in maryland for example the old law required all abortions to 
be approved by a hospital board and performed in a hospital the 
old laws in arizona idaho and wisconsin made all abortions illegal 
except those to save a mothers life in oklahoma the preroe law 
provided for a prison term of up to five years for anyone convicted 
of performing an abortion 
abortion opponents have kept the issue alive in many states as 
much as the courts have allowed two dozen states have passed laws 
that mandate parental consent for abortions for minor women 
parental notification or both and 10 or so are considering such 
bills this year 
all but a dozen states have cut off medicaid financing of 
abortions for poor women in many of those states efforts to 
restrict that money come up year after year in california for 
example the legislature has passed abortionfunding limits every 
year for the last decade only to have them struck down by state 
courts 
fights over such restrictions while often heated and 
disruptive would pale next to the battles that might ensue if the 
justices were to return abortion to state control some observers 
say 
once it goes back to the states and people will be playing 
with real bullets its a whole different ballgame said michael 
friedman a democrat from miami beach in the florida house 
many legislators predict a reversal of roe vs wade would result 
in the issue dominating the legislative and electoral processes in 
many states 
ive always said that if the court overturns on tuesday wed 
introduce legislation on wednesday to outlaw abortions said 
pennsylvania lawmaker stephen freind leader of the antiabortion 
forces in that states general assembly 
any meaningful debate on any other public policy would come to 
a standstill said roger moe majority leader in the minnesota 
senate the question would be are you for or against abortion 
thats how candidates would be picked regardless of how they stand 
on other important matters 
