<TEXT>
chrysler corp has upped the ante in 
what could be a highstakes matchme incentive game by offering 
interestfree financing on twoyear loans for all of its cars 
the nations no 3 automaker made the move monday five days 
after ford motor co challenged the other automakers with 29 
percent financing for twoyear terms general motors corp followed 
fords lead a day later 
interestfree automobile financing was last offered in september 
1986 by american motors corp which chrysler bought less than a 
year later 
chairman ben bidwell of chrysler motors corp the corporations 
carmaking arm called the free financing deal the ultimate in 
apr annual percentage rate programs 
it cant get any lower he added it cant get any 
simpler 
in addition to the low financing for twoyear terms each of the 
big three also expanded and boosted some of their cash rebates and 
offered 59 percent financing for threeyear loans and 69 percent 
for fouryear notes 
ford and gm will write a fiveyear loan for 99 percent 1 
percentage point lower than chryslers rate for a 60month term 
chryslers program runs indefinitely fords expires may 31 and 
gms runs out june 5 
for a customer financing a 13000 car with 1000 down meaning 
a 12000 loan the monthly payments on a twoyear loan would be 
500 under chryslers interestfree incentive and 51524 under 
ford and gms 29 percent plans a twoyear loan at 11 percent a 
common openmarket rate would be 55929 a month 
for a morecommon 48month loan a buyer of either a chrylser 
gm or ford car would pay 28680 under the 69 percent loans 
offered by the big three with a marketrate loan of 11 percent a 
48month loan would come to 316 monthly 
each of the companies acknowledged that the incentives would cut 
into their profits and bidwell said the companys earnings during 
the first six months of 1989 would be below last years levels and 
then rebound in the second half 
but automobile analyst david healy of drexel burnham lambert 
inc of new york disagreed 
i think the gradual increase youve seen in sales incentives 
over the last three or four months will have a significant 
impact he said i think chryslers earnings are likely to be 
flat a few months ago i was looking for a goodsize increase 
the incentive war comes on the heels of unexpectedly low early 
1989 sales and inventories that have been causing some worry but 
no panic among automakers each of the big three automakers set 
ambitious production schedules for the first few months of this 
year and there are no largescale moves to curtail them yet 
car and light truck sales through the first 80 days of 1989 have 
been running 54 percent behind the same period last year the 
secondbest in the industrys history 
sales figures for the first quarter of the year are due out 
today the automakers are hoping that the new incentive programs 
will give sales a boost during april when they usually are strong 
as americans look forward to summer vacations and weekend driving 
trips 
interestfree financing affects only twoyear loans which in 
the past have made up about 12 percent of chrysler credit corps 
business jerry farrell president of loanmaking company said he 
expected that percentage to double with the new program 
he also said the 69 percent interest rate for 48month loans 
down from 89 percent in chryslers previous incentive program 
will attract buyers who may have been considering fiveyear notes 
chrysler unlike ford and gm has not seen a growing number of 
repossessions and loan defaults in the fiveyear loan category 
which makes up about 60 percent of the companys vehicleloan 
business 
the interestfree loan deal was well received by dealers the 
corporation talked with during the weekend said tom pappert vice 
president for sales at chrysler motors 
but the program is bound to face strong criticism from ron 
tonkin president of the national automobile dealers association 
late last week after ford and gm announced their new incentive 
programs tonkin called the incentive war a circus he urged 
automakers to get out of the matchme incentive games and lower 
the prices once and for all and guarantee the public those are the 
prices 
but bob lutz president of chrysler motors said that wont 
work rebates frequently are used to bolster the creditworthiness 
of a potential buyer by increasing their down payment he said 
we would greatly prefer to operate the way we used to operate 
lutz said monday but the reality is that isnt the world 
we live in anymore whether well ever get out of it is anybodys 
guess 
