<DOCNO> AP890404-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
crossed wiring or plumbing problems in fire 
warning and extinguishing systems have been found on 94 boeing 
jetliners the federal aviation administration said today 
the faa said none of the problems directly affected the planes 
airworthiness and all were corrected before the aircraft returned 
to service 
on jan 31 the faa issued an airworthiness directive ordering 
us operators of boeing jets to inspect for possible wiring or 
plumbing problems in fire warning and suppression systems in 
aircraft engines and cargo holds 
the directive was prompted by the discovery of 32 such problems 
in previous checks of boeing planes 
only us operators were required to make the checks but many 
foreign carriers followed suit voluntarily the faa said that of 
the 63 problems found since the directive was issued 36 were 
reported since the last update on march 10 six were found on us 
aircraft and 57 on foreign planes two problems were found on one 
aircraft faa spokesman david duff said 
duff said the names of the foreign carriers would not be 
released because they reported voluntarily and because we feel 
that would hinder the future flow of information 
however air canada has said it found wiring problems on two of 
its 767s australian airlines reported wrong connections on fire 
extinguisher bottles on four of its 737s and japanese television 
network nhk reported last month that problems were found on 19 747s 
and 767s operated by japan air lines and all nippon airways 
at the time of the march 10 faa update boeing co officials 
said they had found an engineering solution to prevent wiring 
problems and were awaiting faa approval for it 
boeing commercial airplanes spokesman craig martin said today 
the engineering changes were undergoing final review at boeing 
before submission to the faa for its approval he said the changes 
involve the wiring and plumbing connectors to physically 
differentiate the connectors so it will be much more difficult to 
connect them improperly 
the initial crossconnection problems were reported about a year 
ago since then boeing has made a lot of progress looking at our 
assembly procedures in the factory and the functional tests in the 
factories martin said 
boeing also is examining its maintenance manuals to see if 
instructions need to be clarified and whether there is a need to 
test the extinguisher and warning system functions when maintenance 
is carried out he said 
martin said in the vast majority of the problems reported 
the fire suppression systems still worked both the cargo hold and 
engine fire extinguisher systems have backups 
the faa said today that 19 of the 63 problems were found in the 
engine fire warning and supression systems of those 10 were found 
on 737300s and 737400s three on 767s five on 757s and one on a 
747 
fortyfour problems were found in cargo compartment fire warning 
and extinguishing systems including 30 on 747s one on a 757 and 
13 on 767s 
the 32 problems found before the jan 31 directive was issued 
involved 12 us and 20 foreign aircraft eight of those involved 
engine systems including four on 737300s and 737400s three on 
757s and one on a 747 the remaining 24 involved cargo hold 
systems seven on 757s and 17 on 767s 
the faa said that of the total 95 problems 68 concerned wiring 
with 24 such problems in engines and 44 in cargo compartments the 
remaining 27 were fire extinguisher plumbing problems with three 
in engines and 24 in cargo compartments all the plumbing problems 
were on 767s 
</TEXT>
